MLB Season Simulation: Quantifying the Impact of the Starting Pitcher and Recent Team Performance

Will Hoover, J.P. Daliere, Roy Son

2025-10-27

Executive Report

If the 2024 MLB season were simulated many times, how often would the Los Angeles Dodgers come out on top? If we were to simulate When accounting for the potential factors such as the ability of a starting pitcher or recent team performance, how would the results change? We will run three statistical models that simulate the 2024 MLB season based on these identification factors, and then select the best model based on both model performance metrics and qualitative considerations, while considering how the performance of the Dodgers varies with each model.

The first simulation method involved estimating team strengths based on only the record of each team vs every team they played against during the season, and due to its simplicity, served as a baseline model to be compared against. Across 100 simulations, the Dodgers finished with the most wins 32 times.

The next method attempted to incorporate the performance of the teams starting pitchers to estimate team strengths. Strengths were estimated by computing the difference between ERAs of the home and away team starting pitcher. Across 100 simulations, the Dodgers finished with the most wins 52 times, suggesting that the Dodgers win totals are elevated when team strengths are based on pitcher performance.

The third simulation method extended the ideas of pitcher performance, but added a metric that considered team form, the proportion of games won over a teams last 15 games. Across 100 simulations, the Dodgers finished with the most wins 52 times. This was possibly due to the fact that team form was found to be a statistically insignificant metric, either due to the 15 game threshold being the incorrect length of games, or that starting pitcher performances are generally independent of the form of the rest of the team, as starting pitchers play much less often than the rest of the team.

Ultimately, the simulation accounting for recent team performance as well as pitching strength was deemed to be the most effective simulation model due to its most optimal results in statistical performance metrics. The baseline model performed the worst in terms of performance metrics, while the form-based pitching model slightly outperformed the non-form pitching model. Based on initial results, it appears the Dodgers are a much more dominant team when team strengths are estimated from pitching performance, suggesting that their recent dominance of the league is a byproduct of their star-studded rotation.

How often would they finish in the top 5? Was their league leading 98 wins a fluke? Or were the Dodgers truly a dominant force?

Furthermore, lets consider different ways to estimate team strengths. In recent times, the Dodgers feature a staff of talented pitchers, including Clayton Kershaw, Tyler Glasnow, Blake Snell, Shohei Ohtani, and many more. If we were able to allow our estimated strength values to depend on the abilities of these pitchers, and for other teams their pitchers, would the Dodgers be expected to win more or less than before?

This concept can be extended to a wide variety of outcomes, such as player salary, the specific batting order used, recent team performance, and many more variables. For this analysis, we will quantify the impact of a teams starting pitcher, their home field advantage, and their performance in recent games as a metric to predict the probability of that team winning a game versus a specific opponent. In light of the Dodgers winning their second straight World Series (sigh), we will use these models to question or confirm their continued regular season dominance. Was their recent dominance merely a fluke, or is the all star ensemble of baseball talent under performing?

Bradley Terry Modeling

The Bradley Terry model is a simple way of computing the probability of pairwise events, for example the likelihood of team i beating team j. For application to a league of p teams, each playing n games. The model assumes that each team \(j = 1, ..., p\) has an underlying strength value \(\lambda_j\), which is a value that represents the strength of team j compared to a reference team which has its strength set to 0.

The probability that team i beats team j is defined as such. \[\mathbb{P}(\textrm{team i beats team j}) = \frac{e^{\lambda_{i}}}{e^{\lambda_{i}} + e^{\lambda_{j}}} = \frac{1}{1 + e^{-1 \times (\lambda_{i} - \lambda_{j})}}\]

Now consider the possibility that there is some value that only exists for one team in the match up, for example, home field advantage. We introduce an additional parameter \(\lambda_0\), that accounts for home field advantage. This value is of course only relevant for the home team.

\[\mathbb{P}(\textrm{team j beats i at j's home}) = \frac{e^{\lambda_{j} + \lambda_{0}}}{e^{\lambda_{j} + \lambda_{0}} + e^{\lambda_{i}}} = \begin{align} &= \frac{1}{1 + e^{-1 \times (-\lambda_{0} + \lambda_{i} - \lambda_{j})}}. \end{align}\]

Furthermore, when considering the covariates of interest such as pitching performance recent team form, each teams \(\lambda\) can be computed in the following form.

\[\lambda_{j} = u_{j} + \boldsymbol{\mathbf{x}}_{j}^{\top}\beta,\] \(\boldsymbol{\mathbf{x}}_{j}^{\top}\) represents a vector of team-level covariates and \(u_j\) is an intercept. In a sense, computing \(\lambda_j\) turns into a fancy regression model. This is the generalized form that will be implemented for computing the effects of pitcher performance and team form.

Data Construction and Cleaning

Data incorporated in this analysis was sourced from baseball-reference.com, and fangraphs.com through the baseballr package, as well as player identification codes from (https://www.smartfantasybaseball.com/tools/).

One of the premier tasks of a data scientist is properly cleaning, pre-processing, and preparing data before any form of advanced analysis can be performed. Pre-processing and cleaning proved to be both a crucial and important part of the project, due to several key factors.

Unfortunately, we could not find a data frame formatted where every row was a game instance that contained information about both the game outcome and starting pitcher stats in a clean form, However, information was found for each subcategory, one for game results, and a second containing pitching information were recovered. Thus, a data frame containing info about the results and pitchers for each game was created by creating data frames for information about each game and outcome, and a second that recorded information about every starting pitcher outing for the season. Finally, the two data frames were combined to achieve the desired result.

Game Logs

To facilitate in the scraping of web data, a Statcast helper function called annual_statcast_query was implemented.

## Code modified from Bill Petti's original annual Statcast scraper:
## Main change is in the column names of the fielders

annual_statcast_query <- function(season) {
  
  data_base_column_types <- 
    readr::read_csv("https://app.box.com/shared/static/q326nuker938n2nduy81au67s2pf9a3j.csv")
  
  dates <- 
    seq.Date(as.Date(paste0(season, '-03-01')),
             as.Date(paste0(season, '-12-01')), 
             by = '4 days')
  
  date_grid <- 
    tibble::tibble(start_date = dates, 
                   end_date = dates + 3)
  
  safe_savant <- 
    purrr::safely(baseballr::scrape_statcast_savant)
  
  payload <- 
    purrr::map(.x = seq_along(date_grid$start_date),
               ~{message(paste0('\nScraping week of ', date_grid$start_date[.x], '...\n'))
                 payload <- 
                   safe_savant(start_date = date_grid$start_date[.x], 
                               end_date = date_grid$end_date[.x], 
                               type = 'pitcher')
                 return(payload)
               })
  
  payload_df <- purrr::map(payload, 'result')
  
  number_rows <- 
    purrr::map_df(.x = seq_along(payload_df),
                  ~{number_rows <- 
                    tibble::tibble(week = .x, 
                                   number_rows = length(payload_df[[.x]]$game_date))
                  }) %>%
    dplyr::filter(number_rows > 0) %>%
    dplyr::pull(week)
  
  payload_df_reduced <- payload_df[number_rows]
  
  payload_df_reduced_formatted <- 
    purrr::map(.x = seq_along(payload_df_reduced), 
               ~{cols_to_transform <- 
                 c("pitcher", "fielder_2", "fielder_3",
                   "fielder_4", "fielder_5", "fielder_6", "fielder_7",
                   "fielder_8", "fielder_9")
               df <- 
                 purrr::pluck(payload_df_reduced, .x) %>%
                 dplyr::mutate_at(.vars = cols_to_transform, as.numeric) %>%
                 dplyr::mutate_at(.vars = cols_to_transform, function(x) {ifelse(is.na(x), 999999999, x)})
               character_columns <- 
                 data_base_column_types %>%
                 dplyr::filter(class == "character") %>%
                 dplyr::pull(variable)
               numeric_columns <- 
                 data_base_column_types %>%
                 dplyr::filter(class == "numeric") %>%
                 dplyr::pull(variable)
               integer_columns <- 
                 data_base_column_types %>%
                 dplyr::filter(class == "integer") %>%
                 dplyr::pull(variable)
               df <- 
                 df %>%
                 dplyr::mutate_if(names(df) %in% character_columns, as.character) %>%
                 dplyr::mutate_if(names(df) %in% numeric_columns, as.numeric) %>%
                 dplyr::mutate_if(names(df) %in% integer_columns, as.integer)
               return(df)
               })
  
  combined <- payload_df_reduced_formatted %>%
    dplyr::bind_rows()
  
  return(combined)
}

Pitchers

Starting pitcher data was sourced from fangraphs.com, and all players who played in the 2024 season and their fangraphs ids were extracted. If they were a pitcher, then their id would correspond to complete data using the function fg_pitcher_game_logs(playerid = key, year = 2024). If not, the for loop skips over the id, and every successful ids data was appended to a larger data frame.

Ids were loaded from a library more complete than the Chadwick Register, as the Chadwick Register had a plethora of missing fan graph ids for many relevant players.

sfbb = read.csv("C:/Users/willh/OneDrive/Documents/STAT 479/Project 2/SFBB-Player-ID-Map.csv")

The ids from the updated baseball mapping library were extracted

all_pitchers_df2 <- data.frame()

for(key in sfbb_keys) {
  tryCatch({
    pitcher_data <- fg_pitcher_game_logs(playerid = key, year = 2024)
    
    if(!is.null(pitcher_data) && nrow(pitcher_data) > 0) {
      pitcher_data$playerid <- key  # add identifier
      all_pitchers_df2 <- bind_rows(all_pitchers_df2, pitcher_data)
    }
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("Error with playerid ", key, ": ", e$message)

One massive setback associated with this method is that the library containing all the players had many missing values for only the fan graphs ids, yet less missing ids than in the Chadwick Register. It was determined as the number of starts made in the run with just ids from the library was less than the total number of games played.

Thus, after the initial id looping, all the present starting pitcher data at the team level was examined and cross referenced to statistics on baseball reference.com to determine which pitchers were missing from the library. Then, the ids were retrieved manually from fan graphs for each missing player.

In total, 24 pitchers who had started a game in the 2024 season were missing a fan graphs id in the library. These missing ids and the initial set of ids were combined and the pitching data was thus retrieved for the super set, resulting in the correct number of pitching starts.

Merging the Dataframes

With two data frames of equal size, we are now ready to combine these two frames into one representative data frame. Each row in the frame represents a single game, with information about each team, the outcome of the game, the home and away team and pitchers, as well as ERASs, innings pitched, and earned runs of each pitcher. The challenge was devising a way to join the two data sets so that no data was lost. It was thus decided to break up the pitching data set into home and away pitchers, and then complete two separate joins.

home_pitchers = starting_pitchers_final_short %>%
  filter(H_A == "H") %>%
  arrange(Date_Numeric, Home_Tm) %>%
  distinct(Date_Numeric, Home_Tm, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(PlayerName, playerid, ERA, IP, ER, Date_Numeric, Home_Tm) %>%
  rename(Home_Pitcher = PlayerName,
         Home_Pitcher_ID = playerid,
         Home_Pitcher_ERA = ERA,
         Home_Pitcher_IP = IP,
         Home_Pitcher_ER = ER,)

away_pitchers = starting_pitchers_final_short %>%
  filter(H_A == "A") %>%
  arrange(Date_Numeric, Away_Tm) %>%
  distinct(Date_Numeric, Away_Tm, .keep_all = TRUE) %>%
  select(PlayerName, playerid, ERA, IP, ER, Date_Numeric, Away_Tm) %>%
  rename(Away_Pitcher = PlayerName,
         Away_Pitcher_ID = playerid,
         Away_Pitcher_ERA = ERA,
         Away_Pitcher_IP = IP,
         Away_Pitcher_ER = ER,)

# Join twice, once for the home pitchers, once for away
game_log_with_pitchers = game_log %>%
  left_join(home_pitchers, by = c("Date_Numeric", "Home_Tm")) %>%
  left_join(away_pitchers, by = c("Date_Numeric", "Away_Tm"))

As one might have noticed, throughout the data frame the same game appears twice. For example, Thus, our final step is removing duplicate games, and this is done by simply selecting one instance of each game, in this case, where the home team is the team of interest corresponding to the original game_log data set. Columns are selected in a way such that a desired order in which they appear occurs.

games_with_pitchers = game_log_with_pitchers %>%

Model 1: Baseline Bradley Terry Model

Now we are ready to fit the initial, baseline Bradley Terry Model. This version only considers the record of the team and their respective match ups. To fit the model, each possible match up is recorded and the total wins/losses for each match up is recorded. The home and away team is also set up into a factorized form

unique_teams = sort(unique(c(game_log$Home_Tm, game_log$Away_Tm)))

all_matchups =
  game_log %>% 
  dplyr::group_by(Home_Tm, Away_Tm) %>% 
  dplyr::summarise(
    Home_Win = sum(Home_Winner),
    Away_Win = sum(Away_Winner), .groups = 'drop') %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(
    Home_Tm = factor(Home_Tm, levels = unique_teams),
    Away_Tm = factor(Away_Tm,levels = unique_teams))

The lambda values are then estimated. The Arizona Diamondbacks are used as the reference team, although in practice it doesnt matter which team is held constant, as the lambdas for all other teams adjust in accordance and the same win/loss probabilities are yielded.

# Arizona Diamondbacks are used as the reference team
fit1 = BradleyTerry2::BTm(
  outcome = cbind(Home_Win, Away_Win),
  player1 = Home_Tm, player2 = Away_Tm,
  refcat = "ARI",
  data = all_matchups
)
lambda_hat1 = BradleyTerry2::BTabilities(fit1)

Now to simulate a season, we must replicate a data frame for the number of seasons we wish to replicate. Due to computation time, only 100 simulations are completed, as it takes considerable time ro replicate each season, as we create a whole new data frame for each simulation.

To simulate a game using the theoretical probabilities, for each match up we generate a random number between 0 and 1. If this number is lower than the BTM winning probability for the Home team, then the home team is awarded a victory, and the away team a loss.

n_sims = 100

simulation_results = replicate(n_sims, (games_with_pitchers_btm1 
                               %>% mutate(
                      random_number = runif(n()), 
                      Home_Simulated_Win = ifelse(Home_Win_Prob > random_number, 1, 0), 
                      Away_Simulated_Win = 1 - Home_Simulated_Win)
                               ), simplify = FALSE)
head(simulation_results, n = 10)

Simulation results are grouped into one single data frame.

simulation_df = bind_rows(simulation_results, .id = "sim_id")

Assessing Model Performance

We will now assess model accuracy by running metrics that output values representing weighted inaccuracy of predictions.

Brier Scoring and Log-Loss attempt to measure the inaccuracy of a prediction by measuring how far the predicted value \(\hat{p}\) is from the observed value \(Y\), in other words, penalizing very inaccurate predictions. Each metric does this in slightly different ways, yet the general idea remains the same.

Brier score computes the penalty via the following formula. This value is large when \(\hat{p}\) is close to 1 and \(Y\) is 0, and vise versa, therefore outputting a higher value when the prediction is far off from the observed value. Brier score is mathematically bounded between 0 and 1, where a score closer to represents a model that makes less wildly inaccurate predictions.

\[\text{Brier} = n^{-1}\sum_{i = 1}^{n}{(y_{i} - \hat{p}_{i})^2}.\]

brier <- function(y, phat){
  return(mean( (y - phat)^2))
}

Log-Loss builds on the intuition behind the Brier score by penalizing aggressively wrong predictions even more. While Brier score is bounded betweem 0 and 1, Log-Loss can be infinitely large, since as \(\hat{p}_{i} \rightarrow 0,\), \(y_{i} \times \log{\hat{p}_{i}} \rightarrow -\infty.\).

\[\textrm{LogLoss} = -1 \times \sum_{i = 1}^{n}{\left[ y_{i} \times \log(\hat{p}_{i}) + (1 - y_{i})\times\log(1-\hat{p}_{i})\right]}.\]

logloss <- function(y, phat){
  
  if(any(phat < 1e-12)) phat[phat < 1e-12] <- 1e-12
  if(any(phat > 1-1e-12)) phat[phat > 1-1e-12] <- 1-1e-12
  return(-1 * mean( y * log(phat) + (1-y) * log(1-phat)))
}

To successfully compute the scores, minor adjustments are made to the data frame, such as representing the home and away team as numerical factors.

A helper function to fit the theoretical home win probabiliteis was also created.

lambda_hat = BTabilities(fit1)
Home_Win_Prob = function(home_team, away_team){
  diff_latent_strengths = lambda_hat[home_team, "ability"] - lambda_hat[away_team, "ability"]
  return(1 / (1 + exp(-1 * (diff_latent_strengths))))
}

To compute the Log Loss and Brier Score, we divide the data into random testing and training splits, and for each simulation we fit the Bradley Terry model and compute log loss and brier score. We then take the average brier score and logloss over every simulation.

n_sims1 = 100
n1 = nrow(tmp_df)
n_train1 = floor(0.75 * n1) 
n_test1 = n1 - n_train1

test_brier = rep(NA, times = n_sims1)
test_logloss = rep(NA, times = n_sims1)

for(r in 1:n_sims1){
  set.seed(479 + r)
  train_data = 
    tmp_df %>% 
    slice_sample(n = n_train1)
  test_data =
    tmp_df %>% 
    dplyr::anti_join(y = train_data, by = "game_id")
  
  fit1 = BradleyTerry2::BTm(
  outcome = cbind(Home_Winner, Away_Winner),
  player1 = Home_Tm, player2 = Away_Tm,
  refcat = "ARI",
  id = "team",
  data = train_data)
  
  lambda_hat = BTabilities(fit1)
  test_preds1 = test_data %>% mutate(home_win_prob = Home_Win_Prob(Home_Tm, Away_Tm))
  
  test_logloss[r] = logloss(test_preds1$Home_Winner, test_preds1$home_win_prob)
  test_brier[r] = brier(test_preds1$Home_Winner, test_preds1$home_win_prob)
}

Model 2: Adjusting Based on the Starting Pitcher and Home Team Advantage

We will now adjust the initial model based on starting pitcher performance as well as home field advantage. For this model, pitcher performance will be quantified as a function of both the home and away teams pitchers, more specifically, through a difference in their ERAs, or earned run averages.

Although there is a multitude of statistics to choose from when quantifying pitcher performance, ERA was chosen due to its recognizability and simplicity. ERA is defined as the following, where Earned Runs are runs that are scored without a defensive error, therefore being the responsibility of the pitcher.

\[ERA = \frac{Earned \space Runs}{Innings \space Pitched} * 9\]

Naming conventions with the 2 are used to avoid the possibility of overlapping variables, data frames, and functions, as each model was built on a separate local machine.

Data frame is loaded and arranged by date.

season_2024 = read.csv("games_with_pitchers.csv")

season_2024 = season_2024 %>%
  arrange(Date, row_number())

To properly fit the Bradley Terry model, similar prepossessing steps were taken as in the first model, such as representing each teams home and away status in a factorized form, as well as mutation of the ERA strength statistic, which is simply the difference between home and away ERAs.

Bradley_Terry = season_2024 %>%
  transmute(
    home.team = factor(Home_Tm),
    away.team = factor(Away_Tm),
    home.win = as.integer(Home_Winner),
    away.win = as.integer(Away_Winner),
    at.home_home = 1,
    at.home_away = 0,
    era_difference_raw = Home_Pitcher_ERA - Away_Pitcher_ERA
  )%>% 
  filter(!is.na(era_difference_raw)) %>%
  mutate(era_difference = era_difference_raw - mean(era_difference_raw, na.rm=TRUE))
data_frame = data.frame(
  home.win = Bradley_Terry$home.win,
  away.win = Bradley_Terry$away.win
)

data_frame$home.team = data.frame(
  team = Bradley_Terry$home.team,
  at.home = 1,
  era = + Bradley_Terry$era_difference/2
)

data_frame$away.team = data.frame(
  team = Bradley_Terry$away.team,
  at.home = 0,
  era = - Bradley_Terry$era_difference/2
)

With prepossessing steps complete, the Bradley Terry Model can be fit using a similar syntax as before, this time including the new predictors of interest.

Assessing Model Performance

We now assess model performance using the same metrics as before with similar methodology.

Model performance is calcuated using virtually the same methodology as for the baseline model.

set.seed(50)

n = nrow(games_with_pitchers)

cv_log = data.frame()

for(r in 1:100){
  train_idx = sample(1:n, size = floor(0.75*n), replace = FALSE)
  train_df = games_with_pitchers[train_idx,]
  test_df = games_with_pitchers[-train_idx,]
  unik_teams = sort(unique(c(train_df$Home_Tm, train_df$Away_Tm)))
  
  results_train = train_df %>%
    rename(home_team = Home_Tm, away_team = Away_Tm) %>% 
  mutate(
    home_team = factor(home_team, levels = unik_teams), 
    away_team = factor(away_team,levels = unik_teams),
    home_athome = 1,
    away_athome = 0)
  
  results_test = test_df %>%
    rename(home_team = Home_Tm, away_team = Away_Tm)%>%
    mutate(
      home_team = factor(home_team, levels = unik_teams),
      away_team = factor(away_team, levels = unik_teams),
      home_athome =1,
      away_athome = 0
    )
  tmp_df <- data.frame(Home_Winner = results_train$Home_Winner, Away_Winner = results_train$Away_Winner)
  
  tmp_df$home_team <- data.frame(team = results_train$home_team, at_home = results_train$home_athome, pitcher_era = results_train$Home_Pitcher_ERA)
  
  tmp_df$away_team <- data.frame(team = results_train$away_team, at_home = results_train$away_athome, pitcher_era = results_train$Away_Pitcher_ERA)
  
  fit_sim <-
  BTm(
    outcome = cbind(Home_Winner, Away_Winner),  
    player1 = home_team, player2 = away_team,
    formula = ~ team + at_home + pitcher_era,
    refcat = "ARI",
    id = "team",
    data = tmp_df) 
  
  abil_mat = BTabilities(fit_sim)
  abil = abil_mat[,"ability"]
  beta_home = coef(fit_sim)["at_home"]
  beta_era = coef(fit_sim)["pitcher_era"]
  
  home = as.character(results_test$home_team)
  away = as.character(results_test$away_team)
  difference_in_abil = abil[home] - abil[away]
  difference_era = results_test$Home_Pitcher_ERA - results_test$Away_Pitcher_ERA
  
  phat = plogis(difference_in_abil + beta_home + difference_era * beta_era) 
  
  cv_log = rbind(cv_log,
                 data.frame(iter = r,
                            brier=brier(results_test$Home_Winner, phat),
                            logloss=logloss(results_test$Home_Winner, phat)))
}

Finally, after fitting the Bradley-Terry model with team ability, home field advantage, and starting pitcher effects, we examined the estimated coefficients. Each team has a coefficient relative to Arizona Diamondbacks, with most not being statistically significant individually since the model estimates relative strength conditional on opponents and pitcher effects. The home field effect is estimated at 0.076, slightly increasing log-odds of winning, but with a p-value of 0.17 its not statistically significant.

However, the pitcher ERA effect of -0.235 is highly significant (p < 2e-16), meaning a better starting pitcher ERA strongly increases home team win probability. Cross-validation across 100 randomized 75/25 splits yielded an average Brier score of 0.161 and log loss of 0.521both substantially lower than the simpler models 0.245 and 0.684. Since lower scores generally indicate better performance, adding starting pitcher and home field advantage clearly improves predictions, with pitcher ERA being the key driver of enhanced accuracy.

Model 3: Adjusting Based on Recent Team Performance

BT Model #3: Accounting for Team Form:

The third and final Bradley-Terry Model we built accounts for one additional variable: team form.

Motivation:

Over the course of a 162 game season, it is common for players and teams to go on hot and cold stretches, periods where teams win or lose many more games than expected. Because of this, we question if accounting for recent team performance will make our model more accurate.

Team Form:

We define team form as a teams win rate over their last 15 games.

Team Form = # of Wins over last 15 games / 15 Team Form = \[Team \space Form = \frac{Wins \space Over \space Last \space 15 \space games}{15}\]

1. Building our BT Model #3:

First, we load in the dataframe and execute similar pre-processing steps as in prior models.

unik_teams3 <- sort(unique(c(games_with_pitchers$Home_Tm, games_with_pitchers$Away_Tm)))

results3 <- games_with_pitchers %>% 
  rename(home_team = Home_Tm, away_team = Away_Tm) %>% 
  mutate(
    home_team = factor(home_team, levels = unik_teams3), 
    away_team = factor(away_team,levels = unik_teams3),
    home_athome = 1,
    away_athome = 0) %>% 
  select(Date, game_id, home_team, away_team, Home_Winner, Away_Winner, home_athome, away_athome, Home_Pitcher_ERA, Away_Pitcher_ERA)

Create Home Win Probability Function:

We then define our home win probability function. This will be used to compute theoretical win probabilities for the home team in every regular season game.

It takes six arguments:

  1. home_team
  2. away_team
  3. home_pitcher_ERA
  4. away_pitcher_ERA
  5. home_team_form
  6. away_team_form

It then uses these variables to compute the difference in latent strengths, difference in pitcher ERAs, and difference in team forms, which are plugged into the formula for the probability that team H (the home team) beats team A (the away team) at Hs home.

Home_Win_Prob3 <- function(home_team, away_team, home_pitcher_era, 
                          away_pitcher_era, home_team_form, away_team_form) {
  diff_latent_strengths <- 
    lambda_hat[home_team, "ability"] - lambda_hat[away_team, "ability"]
  
  diff_pitcher_eras <- (home_pitcher_era - away_pitcher_era)
  
  diff_team_forms <- (home_team_form - away_team_form)
  
  return(1/(1 + exp(-1 * (diff_latent_strengths + lambda_home + (diff_pitcher_eras*lambda_pitcher_era) + (diff_team_forms * lambda_form)))))
}

Creating Team Form Variable:

To build our BT model which accounts for team form, we first must derive two new variables: home_team_form and away_team_form.

We derive these team form variables by pivoting our dataframe into a longer format where each row corresponds to a unique team and game. And each row contains information as to whether each team won or lost the game.

We then use this longer dataframe to compute each teams win rate (over their last 15 games). And combine this dataframe (containing team form) with our original dataframe.

# Ensure Date is a proper Date type and games are in order
results3 <- results3 %>%
  mutate(Date = as.Date(Date)) %>%
  arrange(Date)

# Long format: one row per team per game
results_long <- results3 %>%
  mutate(Game_ID = row_number()) %>%
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(home_team, away_team),
    names_to = "Side",
    values_to = "Team"
  ) %>%
  mutate(
    Win = ifelse(Side == "home_team", Home_Winner, Away_Winner)
  ) %>%
  select(Game_ID, Date, Team, Win)

# Compute each team's rolling win rate (last 15 games)
results_form <- results_long %>%
  group_by(Team) %>%
  arrange(Date) %>%
  mutate(
    team_form = map_dbl(seq_along(Win), function(i) {
      past_games <- Win[max(1, i - 15):(i - 1)]
      if (length(past_games) == 0) return(NA_real_)
      mean(past_games)
    })
  ) %>%
  ungroup()

# Join both home and away team form values back to main dataset
results_form <- results_form %>%
  group_by(Game_ID, Date) %>%
  arrange(Game_ID, Date, row_number()) %>%  # ensure order within game
  mutate(team_order = row_number()) %>%
  summarise(
    home_team = Team[team_order == 1],
    away_team = Team[team_order == 2],
    home_winner = Win[team_order == 1],
    away_winner = Win[team_order == 2],
    home_team_form = team_form[team_order == 1],
    away_team_form = team_form[team_order == 2],
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>% 
  rename(game_id = "Game_ID", Home_Winner = "home_winner", Away_Winner = "away_winner")

results3 <- inner_join(results3, results_form)
## Joining with `by = join_by(Date, game_id, home_team, away_team, Home_Winner,
## Away_Winner)`

2. Assessing Model Accuracy:

Individual coefficients and key values are extracted from the model for later use.

We extract the lambdas for the latent team strengths, for home advantage, for team form, and for pitcher Eras. These lambdas will be plugged into our home_win_prob function to obtain theoretical home win probabilities.

lambda_hat <- BTabilities(fit_form3)

lambda_form <- coef(fit_form3)["form"]

Assessing Model Performance

Calculation of model logloss and brier score is essentially the same method as employed for the other models. Divide the data into random testing and training splits, fit the model, append the theoretical probabilities to the data frame,

n_sims <- 100
n_row = nrow(tmp_df3)
n_train <- floor(0.75*n_row)

##Initialize testing log loss vector
test_logloss3 <- rep(NA, times = n_sims)
test_brier3 <- rep(NA, times = n_sims)

for(r in 1:n_sims){
  set.seed(479+r)
  train_data3 <-
    tmp_df3 |>
    dplyr::slice_sample(n = n_train)
  test_data3 <-
    results3 |>
    dplyr::anti_join(y = train_data3, by = "game_id") 

  ##Fit model using training data
  fit_form3 <-
    BTm(
      outcome = cbind(Home_Winner, Away_Winner),  
      player1 = home_team, player2 = away_team,
      formula = ~ team + at_home + pitcher_era + form,
      refcat = "ARI",
      id = "team",
      data = train_data3) 
  
  ##Extract Lambdas
  lambda_hat3 <- BTabilities(fit_form3)
  lambda_home3 <- coef(fit_form3)["at_home"]
  lambda_form3 <- coef(fit_form3)["form"]
  lambda_pitcher_era3 <- coef(fit_form3)["pitcher_era"]
  
  
  ##Make predictions on testing data
  test_preds_df3 <- test_data3 %>% 
    mutate(home_win_prob = Home_Win_Prob3(home_team, away_team, Home_Pitcher_ERA, Away_Pitcher_ERA, home_team_form, away_team_form))
  
  ##Compute log-loss and Brier score and store them in the log-loss and brier score vectors
  test_logloss3[r] <-
    logloss(test_preds_df3$Home_Winner, test_preds_df3$home_win_prob)
  test_brier3[r] <-
    brier(test_preds_df3$Home_Winner, test_preds_df3$home_win_prob)
}

Limitations and Future Considerations

Over fitting is an issue that appears to be inherent in the analysis, as the team strengths are being estimated based on one season and then, that season is re-simulated based off those estimated strengths. Naturally, when simulating that season a large amount of times, the distribution of the wins per team converges to the observed results. How much information do we truly gain through re simulating the same thing weve trained our model on? Additionally, team strengths are estimated off of starting pitcher performances that occurred during that season. This has the effect of simulating earlier games in the season which are partially based off games that happened in the future, which doesnt really make much sense. There is a potential solution for this problem which is touched on in the next limitation.

Another considerable limitation of the model which considered starting pitchers was an inability to implement a feature which computed a delayed rolling average for ERA for each team. The intuition behind this feature is that for the first x, lets say 10 games, a teams average ERA is not representative of the long run average over the 162 game season. To combat this, a delayed rolling average is employed which only starts calculating after the 10th game. Before this mark, the ERAs for each team are fixed at some reasonable, arbitrary constant; a value representative of an average league ERA.

Attempts to implement this feature proved to be quite difficult, and it was ultimately decided to exclude this feature from the model. An apparent side effect of not implementing this feature was a high amount of variance among certain individual game probabilities for the third model. Several games early in the season showed theoretical win probabilities close to 100% or 0%, a value almost certain to be false, as the value suggests that in 100,000 repeated attempts of the game, the opposing team would only win once. Thus, the model has less application to predicting the outcome of individual games as a result of this variance.

Another considerable limitation is the variation among how long a starting pitcher plays for, as well as potential correlation between number of innings pitched and ERA. Generally, starting pitchers pitch less innings when they are giving up too many runs, and pitch longer when they are giving up fewer runs. This variability in innings also affects the portion of the game pitched However, there is potential that this implication is less important than it seems in the sense that bad starting pitchers tend to pitch for shorter times after allowing multiple runs, while good starting pitchers tend to play for longer, as they are less likely to allow runs.

ERA is also not the end all be all statistic for measuring pitcher performance. ERA was used due to its simple format and recognizability, yet there are several other statistics that could be used in adjunct with ERA such as WHIP (Walks plus hits per Inning Pitched), ERA+ which standardizes ERA relative to the performance of other players in the league, and FIP (fielding independent pitching). Perhaps a linear combination of these metrics to quantify pitcher performance would remedy some of the high variance observed in the pitcher adjusted models.

Finally, running only 100 simulations for both evaluating model performance and simulating seasons leads to significant variability in results as opposed to running lets say 100,000 simulations. 100 was chosen due to the fact that it would not cause significant memory and timing issues on the local machine.

Conclusions and Future Considerations

Ultimately, the Bradley-Terry model which accounts for both recent team performance and pitcher performance appears to be the most effective model for season simulation, due to it containing the lowest values for both log loss and brier score as well

When considering future adjustments and improvements for these models, to truly capture the effect that pitching has on the outcome of a game, the other pitchers in the game must be accounted for. Due to the variability of the innings pitched per starting pitcher, the impact that relief pitchers have also varies, yet the total impact pitching has on the game is always the same if both groups are included.

Experimentation with the recent team form metric will also be considered, as although the initial results showed form as insignificant, perhaps this will change when altering the duration of games in which team form is considered. It may also be the case that starting pitcher performance is less dependent on team form of the other players, as starting pitchers dont play nearly as often as everyone else.

Ultimately, it seems that not only has the Dodgers recent dominance not been due to mere chance, but more likely than not that the Dodgers are the dominant force in the league, especially when considering their star-studded lineup of pitchers. Perhaps the shocking results from our simulations express the need for adjustments to the structure of the league, as debates about a potential salary cap and lack of parity roar. Regardless, the results are clear; the Dodgers pitching staff has allowed them to find renewed success in recent times, and as highlighted by our models, their domination could continue even further given the frequency of finishes with the most wins in our simulations.
